EDIT(1)

NAME
    edit - edit a text file

SYNOPSIS
    edit path
    edit path -c command ...

DESCRIPTION
    edit opens path in the SmallOS text editor. The file is loaded from ext2
    if it exists, or created when saved.

    In interactive mode, the status line shows the main keys. F2 saves the
    file. F3 or Esc exits. If the buffer has unsaved changes, F2 saves and
    exits, F3 discards changes, and Esc cancels the quit.

    Arrow keys move the cursor. Home, End, Page Up, Page Down, Backspace,
    Delete, Enter, and normal printable characters edit the buffer.

BATCH COMMANDS
    With -c, edit runs small line-editor commands instead of opening the
    full-screen editor.

    w
        Write the file.

    q
    q!
        Quit batch processing.

    wq
        Write the file and quit batch processing.

    p [first [last]]
        Print all lines, one line, or a range of lines.

    d first [last]
        Delete one line or a range of lines.

    a [line]
        Append input after line. Input continues through following -c
        arguments until a single dot line is seen.

    i [line]
        Insert input before line.

    r line
        Replace one line with input.

EXAMPLES
    edit /tmp/notes.txt
    edit /tmp/notes.txt -c "a" -c "hello" -c "." -c "wq"

NOTES
    edit is intentionally small and line-oriented internally. Very long lines
    may be truncated.
